<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAY 94 / Blair urged to reach accord with top leftwing opponent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair, front-runner in the Labour leadership contest, was urged by
supporters last night to strengthen his candidacy decisively by striking a
deal with one of his leading rivals on the left of the party.
The suggestion came as Mr Blair, shadow home secretary, and Mr Gordon Brown,
shadow chancellor, faced calls from among Labour's so-called modernisers to
resolve possible competing leadership claims quickly.
A clutch of weekend opinion polls confirmed Mr Blair's advantage over other
contenders to succeed Mr John Smith, who died last Thursday. But Mr John
Prescott, the party's employment spokesman, and Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade
and industry secretary, kept open the option of standing as 'traditionalist'
candidates.
Amid intense behind-the-scenes manoeuvrings, the eventual outcome of the
leadership election remained clouded by left-right differences,
long-standing personal rivalries and rival ambitions of leading party
figures.
Despite agreement by all potential candidates not to campaign until after Mr
Smith's funeral on Friday, shadow cabinet members said informal soundings
over the next few days would be critical in shaping the contest.
Bargaining has been complicated by the fact that many trade union leaders
are reluctant to endorse any particular candidate publicly. The introduction
of one-member-one-vote ballots will greatly reduce the influence of union
executives.
The suggestion that Mr Blair might reach an agreement with one of the
traditionalist candidates came as his supporters admitted that the
41-year-old MP for Sedgefield needed to broaden the basis of his support.
Mr Prescott and Mr Cook have made it clear they would find it much easier to
work with Mr Blair as party leader than Mr Brown.
But Mr Brown's friends were claiming powerful support for his candidacy
within the shadow cabinet and among leading figures in the union movement.
They said the bandwagon running in favour of Mr Blair underestimated Mr
Brown's much stronger ties with grassroots Labour supporters.
The pressure on the two leading modernisers to reach an amicable accord
within the next week followed inconclusive discussions last week in which
they staked out their respective claims. They have agreed to reassess their
relative support later this week. Colleagues said there was no pact between
the two but the hope was that one would step aside in favour of the other.
Mr Bryan Gould, heavily defeated in the leadership contest two years ago by
Mr Smith, predicted the outcome of the manoeuvring would be a contest
between Mr Cook and Mr Blair which would be won by the shadow home
secretary.
Union stands aside, Page 7
