<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 94 / Briefcase, Q&amp;A: 'No mystery'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From RAYMOND MOODY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I refer to the first question and answer in your Briefcase column last
week (May 7/8). If no one has heard of the Rule of Three, then it reinforces
my conviction that the common stock of general knowledge can no longer be
counted upon.
There is no mystery about the Rule of Three. It has a sufficiently
established place in the language to figure in the Oxford English
Dictionary, Vol. Q-R, p882. It is defined as 'a method of finding a fourth
number from three given numbers, of which the first is in the same
proportion to the second as the third is to the unknown fourth' - with eight
supporting quotations from 1594 to 1891.
So much for the Rule of Three. The genuine mystery is how the bank concerned
managed to use this simple rule to turn Pounds 9,000 into Pounds 30,000
unless the phrase was invoked as token of a probverbially arcane procedure.
Are we back in Kipling's world of the 'gods of the copybook headings'?
Raymond Moody
Cobb House
Burford
Oxfordshire
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All enquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
