</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Concerns over the government's plans to manage foreign exchange policy after
the introduction of a new currency on July 1 dragged Sao Paulo stock prices
down 3.1 per cent at the close in light trade.
The Bovespa index of the 56 most-active shares ended off 519 at 15,859
points.
Analysts were worried about the performance of Brazilian export firms after
it was reported that the government might freeze the real/dollar exchange
rate at a one-to-one parity after the adoption of the new currency.
Investors are waiting for congress to vote on a presidential decree creating
the country's single price index. It was reported that the vote has been
postponed until next Tuesday.
