<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Inflation data fails to lift
US equities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
More good news on inflation failed to provide stocks with much of a lift
yesterday, even though the data lifted bond prices, writes Patrick Harverson
in New York.
By the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up only 6.84 at 3,659.68,
having spent the entire day no more than a few points either side of opening
values. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's also ended little changed,
up 0.41 at 444.16, while the American Stock Exchange composite finished down
0.78 at 432.57 and the Nasdaq composite down 2.69 at 716.92. Trading volume
was 253m shares, and declines outpaced rises by 1,068 to 1,068.
For the second day, there was some surprisingly good news on inflation.
After Thursday's unexpected 0.1 per cent decline in the April producer price
index, yesterday's news of a 0.1 per cent increase in April's consumer price
index also confounded analysts, who had forecast an increase of 0.3 per cent
in the CPI.
Taken together, the data was the best indication yet that inflation is not a
major threat to financial markets. Yet, apart from a brief surge of buying
at the opening and again mid-morning, stocks did not gain much benefit from
the figures.
This was mostly because bond prices failed to make much headway, as
fixed-income investors turned their attention to next Tuesday's meeting of
the Federal Reserve's policy- making open market committee. The FOMC is
expected to sanction a rate increase at the meeting, and investors are
nervous about how another tightening will be received by the markets.
Although bond prices began to recover later in the day, stock failed to
derive much strength from the Treasury market. In late trading, the
benchmark 30-year bond was up more than half a point, and the yield was down
to 7.481 per cent, yet blue-chip stocks struggled to stay in positive
territory. Secondary indices fared even less well, with the Nasdaq composite
under particular pressure because of weakness in technology stocks.
Among individual issues, Time Warner climbed Dollars 1 to Dollars 38 5/8
amid renewed speculation that the entertainment group faces a possible bid
from its major shareholder, Seagram. Yesterday's story was that Mr Barry
Diller, head of the QVC home shopping channel, had accumulated Time Warner
shares with the intention of backing Seagram.
Philip Morris was another notable gainer, rising Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 52
1/8 on hopes that the company will split its tobacco and food interests.
Sprint firmed Dollars 1/2 to Dollars 36 5/8 on reports that it is discussing
an alliance with Electronic Data Systems which will combine Sprint's
telecommunications know-how with EDS' data-processing power to compete in
the multi-media business. EDS shares edged Dollars  1/8 higher to Dollars
33.
On the Nasdaq market, concern about slow growth in the computer networking
products business hit technology stocks hard. Cisco tumbled Dollars 5 3/4 to
Dollars 23 1/4 , Wellfleet fell Dollars 8 to Dollars 63 1/2 , and 3 Com
dropped Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 55.
Canada
Toronto stock prices closed modestly higher in relatively light trading, to
end a jittery week on a high note. According to preliminary figures, the
TSE-300 index rose 12.83 points, or 0.31 per cent, to close at 4,175.35.
Advancing issues outnumbered declines 411 to 327.
Preliminary volume was 57.039m shares, up from Thursday's 52.933m shares,
and trading value rose to CDollars 532.7m from CDollars 509.4m.
Nine of Toronto's 14 sub-indexes closed higher, led by mining, up 2.1 per
cent as base-metal prices surged. Inco jumped 1 to 33 3/8 on higher nickel
prices.
Mitel Corp lost  3/8 to 5 after the company said its fourth-quarter earnings
fell to CDollars 4.8m.
Oshawa Group reported first-quarter net income up to CDollars 8.9m. Oshawa
Group A shares gained  1/4 to 20.
</TEXT>
