<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 94 / UK Company News: Pearson thought to have pulled out of
library deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pearson, the media and entertainment group, is believed to have pulled out
of a deal to buy the ITC programme library - an acquisition that would have
been worth about Dollars 175m (Pounds 120m).
Pearson, which also owns the Financial Times, was favourite to buy the
library which contains many of the programmes made by Lord Grade, such as
The Prisoner and films such as On Golden Pond.
ITC, with more than 10,000 hours of programmes and films, is owned by Morgan
Private Equity, in turn a subsidiary of HSBC Holdings.
The apparent failure of the deal comes in the same week that Pearson
announced a 'global strategic alliance' with the BBC to launch jointly
satellite television channels in Europe and the rest of the world.
The purchase of such a library would have fitted in well with Pearson's
stated strategy of expanding in the media and entertainment sectors and
concentrating on the acquisition of intellectual property rights.
It has already acquired a significant programme library through the purchase
of Thames, now the largest independent production company in the UK. Pearson
could not be contacted last night to comment on the ITC deal.
</TEXT>
