<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 94 / West to relaunch Bosnia peace plan: US, EU and Russia agree
new drive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS, BRUCE CLARK and AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA, LONDON, SARAJEVO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The foreign ministers of the US, Russia and five members of the European
Union yesterday called for a four-month ceasefire between the warring
parties in Bosnia and the resumption within two weeks of negotiations on a
political settlement.
Meeting in Geneva, the seven ministers put on an impressive show of unity
over Bosnia, though it is clear that important differences of emphasis
remain. In particular, the Europeans secured a reluctant endorsement from
the US that any peace settlement should be based on their formula allocating
51 per cent of Bosnian territory to the newly formed Bosnian-Croat
federation and 49 per cent to the Bosnian Serbs.
Earlier this week the Bosnian and Croat sides agreed in Vienna on a
US-brokered plan which would give their proposed federation 58 per cent of
Bosnia. However, Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of state, said in
Geneva yesterday that the 51/49 per cent split was 'a desirable basis on
which to proceed'.
US officials said privately that the 58 per cent figure was based on the
'maximum possible formula', arrived at by adding all areas where Moslems and
Croats could form a majority of the population. The federation's borders
would have to be determined in negotiation with the Bosnian Serbs, they
noted.
Mr Christopher said he thought the warring parties would attend the
reconvened peace talks, to be held under the aegis of the five-nation
'contact group' (US, Russia, France, Britain and Germany). The Bosnian Serbs
have said the lifting of United Nations sanctions against Serbia must be a
precondition of resuming talks, a demand the ministers yesterday rejected as
'unacceptable'.
The ministers, from the 'contact group' countries plus Greece and Belgium,
said sanctions would be progressively eased only in response to the 'good
faith implementation' of a peace settlement.
The communique also calls for the ceasefire accord to include the separation
of forces, the withdrawal of heavy weapons and the 'interposition' of
Unprofor troops, a move which would require further reinforcement of UN
peacekeepers.
In Bosnia itself, fighting between Serb and Moslem forces was reported to be
escalating sharply in the north of the republic. Serb sources reported heavy
losses in clashes round the mouth of the Ozren pocket, a Serb mountain
stronghold.
It remains unclear whether yesterday's show of unity in Geneva can overcome
the escalating war of words over Bosnia between politicians in Moscow and
Washington.
The Russian parliament yesterday urged President Boris Yeltsin to lift the
arms embargo against Serbia unilaterally if any other country began sending
arms to Bosnia. This was an angry response to a US Senate resolution
supporting sales to the Moslem leadership in Sarajevo.
The state Duma, or lower house of parliament, voted 270-1 for the
resolution, which also told the Russian government to seek a negotiated end
to all sanctions against rump Yugoslavia, which consists of Serbia and
Montenegro.
A senior Bosnian military source acknowledged yesterday that the Moslem-led
government army received raw material for ammunition from Iran and anti-tank
rockets of unspecified origin, AP reports from Sarajevo.
The army source claimed hundreds of anti-tank rockets, allegedly of American
manufacture, reached the Croatian coast aboard a ship from Brazil.
</TEXT>
