<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / London Stock Exchange: GrandMet falls on Pounds 40m hit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, PETER JOHN and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Food and drinks group Grand Metropolitan stood out as the chief casualty
among leading stocks in London as the market reacted nervously to a shock
Pounds 40m charge included in trading figures announced yesterday.
The results were in line with most estimates but the group reported lower
stock levels at its IDV unit in the US.
However, most sector specialists remained enthusiastic on the group's
end-of-year figures, saying these would be helped by an unexpectedly low tax
charge and a boost in profits from the Burger King subsidiary. Ms Michelle
Proud of NatWest Securities summed up the general feeling: 'There was a lot
of good news but the bad news hit everyone for six.'
Analysts' forecasts were cut accordingly, although earnings per share
estimates were maintained and in some cases lifted slightly. Kleinwort
Benson moved to Pounds 959m for the current year from Pounds 979m but kept
its earnings estimate to 31.9p. SGST dropped by Pounds 40m to Pounds 950m
but raised the eps figure a penny to 3.2p. UBS held steady at Pounds 995m
and raised its earnings to 33.4p, while NatWest Securities moved to Pounds
940m and 32p of earnings.
GrandMet slid sharply to close 26 lower at 457p on exceptionally heavy
turnover of 11m. Dealers said there was heavy switching into Guinness, which
improved 5 to 498p.
</TEXT>
