<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / World Commodities Prices: Wool
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Wool offerings in the closing weeks of the Australian selling season are
normally low and this week auctions were held on only two instead of the
normal three days. Prices moved sharply ahead for finer merinos, and the
market indicator rose above the 600 cent mark which many feel provides the
prospect of economic production for most wool growers. The Wool
international market indicator was 603 cents at the close, compared with 587
a week before. Currency developments have tended to underline the rise in
wool costs in most wool using countries in the past week or so. Recognition
of a rising price trend for wool is obvious among those trading near to the
raw wool end of the trade, but manufacturers and retailers are proving more
difficult to convince that high prices must now be paid.
