<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
First-quarter losses at Thomson Corporation, the Canadian publishing and
travel group, deepened to USDollars 63m, or 11 cents a share, against a loss
of USDollars 59m, or 10 cents, last time.
It blamed slack demand in the travel market during the winter. Newspapers,
however, remained profitable, with better advertising in North America.
The final loss was struck on revenues of USDollars 1.12bn against USDollars
1.07bn. Seasonal weakness in many operations usually bring losses in the
first quarter.
The group, which is one of biggest tour operators in the UK and includes
Britannia Airways, had an operating loss of USDollars 34m against a loss of
USDollars 29m.
The newspaper division, which encompasses 116 dailies and 43 weeklies in
North America and regional publications in the UK, posted an operating
profit of USDollars 32m against USDollars 30m. The Toronto Globe and Mail
showed a 5.2 per cent gain in advertising lineage. Thomson said national
advertising was improving across North America.
Textbooks and services to UK newspapers had an operating loss of USDollars
23m against a deficit of USDollars 19m.
