<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / International Company News: Surge at Gap bucks US trend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Gap, the US casual-wear retailer, shrugged off the poor apparel sales
affecting other US stores to report a 53 per cent jump in net profits, from
Dollars 41.5m to Dollars 63.5m, for the first quarter to April.
The San Francisco-based company attributed the improvement mainly to better
margins, largely resulting from a switch to more feminine-looking clothes
for women in its main Gap stores.
The number of stores opened rose from 1,319 to 1,398 at the end of the
quarter. Of these, 848 were Gap, 179 Banana Republic, 324 GapKids and 47 Old
Navy Clothing Co or Gap Warehouse. Outside North America, it had 44 stores
in the UK and three in France.
Total sales rose 17 per cent to Dollars 752m, while sales at stores open a
year earlier rose 7 per cent. Earnings per share rose from 29 cents to 44
cents.
Gap said one factor behind the improvement in margins was the reduction in
promotional activity compared with last year's quarter. This meant more
goods had been sold at the full price, it said.
More significantly, the company had a good response to its shift away from
unisex, basic clothing such as T-shirts and jeans to more gender-specific
merchandise, particularly for women. The stores now stock more skirts,
dresses and embroidered tops.
Gap has also launched a retailing format called Old Navy Clothing Co for
shoppers who find the group's other stores too expensive. It will gradually
replace the Gap Warehouse chain.
</TEXT>
