<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / UK Company News: New auditor for Enterprise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Enterprise Computer Holdings, the Berkshire-based computer services company,
yesterday said it had asked KPMG Peat Marwick, its auditor, to resign over a
fee dispute.
The company will announce in the next few days the name of a replacement
'Big Six' firm of accountants which has agreed to carry out the audit for
considerably less than KPMG's proposed fee.
Mr Les McNeill, chief executive, said: 'We had a dispute over fees that
became rather prolonged. I felt we were being significantly disadvantaged
and it was time to part ways. We had a fiscal and a moral responsibility to
our shareholders.'
He said KPMG had originally agreed to an audit fee for the current financial
year and then added a further 30 per cent. The firm also wanted to charge an
additional Pounds 12,000 for the previous year's audit.
The increases brought the proposed audit bill to about Pounds 80,000.
KPMG's filing at Companies House states the reason for the resignation was:
'We have not been paid in full for agreed outstanding invoices nor have we
been able to agree to audit fee for the year ended March 31 1994.'
Mr McNeill said he believed the KPMG fee should have been lower, given the
substantial restructuring of the company in the last few months which should
have simplified the audit.
He stressed that he had no criticism of the firm's skills or
professionalism, but that 'right now this company watches cost, cost and
cost.'
</TEXT>
