<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 94 / UK Company News: Halkin expects to return to dividend list
this year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shareholders in Halkin Holdings, the former Hoskins Brewery recently taken
over by Mr Howard Hodgson, the funerals entrepreneur, are likely to receive
their first dividend in more than five years by the end of 1994.
Mr David Moffat, finance director, said yesterday the group expected to pay
a dividend which showed a yield of between 2 per cent and 3 per cent on the
shares in December. Yesterday's closing price of 61p, a rise of 2p, would
imply a net pay-out of roughly 1.2p.
Hoskins Brewery has had a chequered past, with several attempts by
discontented shareholders to remove management. Mr Hodgson bought into the
company last year, aiming to transform it into a mini-conglomerate. Mr
Moffat said the group would pursue acquisitions this year.
Halkin revealed its first set of results since the takeover and the Pounds
15m rights issue-funded purchase of two businesses - Ronson, the lighter and
household aerosol group; and Clifford, which supplies branded goods to the
duty-free market. Both business had met their profits targets of Pounds 1.5m
and Pounds 1m respectively.
The results, which cover only Hoskins Brewery as the other divisions were
bought after the year-end, showed a Pounds 998,000 loss for the nine months
to December 31, on sales of Pounds 478,000.
